  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Information saves lives: Cholera Response in Central African Republic</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="2">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">In the Central African Republic (CAR), FM radio is a major source of information for communities.  Based on a recent USAID funded survey entitled &#x201C;National Access to Media and Information Needs Survey of the CAR&quot;, Internews understands that the CAR population mainly receive information through radio.
Internews will seek to work with national and community radio stations to strengthen the health information environment and provide crucial information to those affected by the ongoing Cholera epidemic in most affected zones along Oubangui River (Ombella M&apos;Poko, Lobaye, Ouaka, Nana Grebizi prefectures and Bangui). The purpose of the project is to provide communities exposed to and affected by the recent Cholera epidemic, with a wide range of life-saving health information through radio in order to contribute to the reduction of mortality and spread of the disease across the country.  
The potential 3 month project intends to increase the quality and quantity of informative and engaging cholera related media content available to Central African Citizens on the aforementioned affected zones. Internews will put in place structures within traditional media to promote informed citizen dialogue on health, water, sanitation and hygiene and will find alternative ways to disseminate the same information to citizens living in remote areas, such as disseminating content through motorbikes or boats. The project also intends to open two-way information flows between citizens, affected communities, humanitarian organizations, the CAR Government as well as media and health responders. Our media and communicating with communities efforts will galvanize community buy-in in strong support of emergency responses against cholera.</narrative>
  </description>
